{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486768"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:44:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:44:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"172"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/172"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.77,0.01,0.03,0.09,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"172"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77204"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/172"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"172"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62711"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"166"},{"type":"tags","id":"183"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3803"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9589"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"70"},{"type":"contributions","id":"513"},{"type":"contributions","id":"582"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42014"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43786"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77204"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 31-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-week history of increasing fatigue. She reports constant vague abdominal discomfort and dizziness on standing. She has no fever, nausea, or vomiting. She has a medical history of type 1 diabetes mellitus and ulcerative colitis. Her medications include prednisolone 50 mg daily for 12 weeks, sulfasalazine 1 g twice daily, insulin glargine, insulin aspart, and a combined oral contraceptive pill. Three months ago, she had a flare of ulcerative colitis requiring high-dose oral prednisolone. Her blood glucose levels have been unexpectedly low despite no changes to her insulin regimen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe started a new stressful job eight weeks ago and has missed several doses of her medications due to her busy schedule. On examination, she appears tired. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 105/65 mmHg supine and 85/50 mmHg standing, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adrenal insufficiency","Major depressive disorder","Peptic ulcer disease","Autonomic neuropathy","Inflammatory bowel disease flare"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Eadrenal insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E secondary to abrupt reduction in long-term glucocorticoid therapy. The combination of fatigue, postural hypotension, abdominal pain, and unexplained hypoglycaemia is highly suggestive. Long-term exogenous steroid use suppresses the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis, making patients dependent on replacement therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMajor depressive disorder\u003C/strong\u003E could explain fatigue, but would not account for the postural hypotension or unexplained hypoglycaemia. Additionally, there are no reported mood symptoms or changes in sleep, appetite, or concentration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeptic ulcer disease\u003C/strong\u003E might cause abdominal pain, but would typically be episodic and related to meals. It would not explain the postural hypotension or hypoglycaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutonomic neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in type 1 diabetes and could explain the postural hypotension, but would not account for the abdominal pain or unexpected hypoglycaemia. It typically develops over many years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory bowel disease flare\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with diarrhoea, bloody stools, and more severe abdominal pain. The patient\u0027s symptoms developed while tapering steroids rather than showing signs of active colitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to diagnosis is recognising that rapid withdrawal or missed doses of long-term steroids can precipitate adrenal insufficiency. These patients require careful monitoring and gradual dose reduction to allow recovery of their endogenous cortisol production.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Secondary adrenal insufficiency can result from rapid tapering or missed doses of long-term glucocorticoid therapy.","Classic symptoms of adrenal insufficiency include fatigue, postural hypotension, abdominal pain, and hypoglycaemia.","Patients on long-term steroids require careful monitoring and gradual dose reduction to prevent adrenal crisis."],"references":["Arlt W, Allolio B. Adrenal insufficiency. Lancet. 2003;361(9372):1881-1893. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(21)00136-7/abstract","Younes AK, Younes NK. Recovery of steroid induced adrenal insufficiency. Transl Pediatr. 2017;6(4):269-273. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5682381/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62711"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"172"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62711"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T11:27:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T11:27:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"172"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77204"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/